## When to use
Use this skill when you need to monitor your system's network traffic in real-time with a focus on bandwidth usage, packet statistics, and overall performance. It is especially useful for diagnosing network issues or understanding data flow patterns.

## Approach
To continuously monitor network traffic using bmon, start the bmon tool with `shell_exec("bmon --color")` to view live network stats in colorized terminal output. For more detailed analysis, use `ssh_exec_background("bmon -d 1 > /tmp/bmon_output.log")` to log periodic snapshots of traffic data for later review.

## Example
To start monitoring the current interface using bmon and viewing it interactively with colors:
```shell
shell_exec("bmon --color")
```

For background logging every second, save the output in a file for analysis or further processing:
```shell
ssh_exec_background("bmon -d 1 > /tmp/bmon_output.log")
```
## Pitfalls
Ensure that bmon is installed on your system before attempting to use it. Also, be aware that running `bmon` continuously can have some impact on performance, especially on busy systems.